            <p>Office of the Rev. Dr. Vidaver.<lb/>
                Rabbi Preacher B&#39;nae Jeshurun<lb/>
                Cong 34<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St. New York<lb/>
                Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                Philada<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I was exceedingly glad to receive your<lb/> letter.  Seeing <hi rend="underline">your second</hi> article in the<lb/> messenger I thought there was some &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Be as it may believe me that there<lb/> was not and there is not with me any<lb/> ill feeling at all &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>It was not my object either to be a &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> or as you say to fight mere typos when<lb/> writing my first strictness&#44; I merely wanted<lb/> that the people should <sic>no</sic> be imposed upon &#91;&#63;&#93; any<lb/> such humbleness.  As for Luzzatto &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; I would<lb/> be re&#91;&#63;&#93; to truth were to give rise to<lb/> &#33;&#91;Hebrew&#93;.  In the year 62 I had the &#91;Hebrew&#93; to write<lb/> to him on some literary subject<lb/> and the great L. with his wanted modesty replied<lb/> as he used to&#44; to all that asked him questions<lb/> regarding &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  He knew my name from<lb/> the Hebrew and German Periodicals to which<lb/> I from time to time contributed.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am sorry I cannot comply with<lb/> your request regarding the &#91;&#63;&#93; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>since I have not brought along with me<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93; to America&#59; I wrote from memory<lb/> which did not deceive me&#59; and you<lb/> judged and surmised rightly&#8212;about the<lb/> sarcasm.<lb/></p>
            <p>As for Dr. Bondi&#44; I did not yet see<lb/> him this week on account of my not<lb/> being well at present&#44; and am bound<lb/> to keep myself <del>at</del> in doors&#44; but as soon<lb/> I see him I&#39;ll &#91;Hebrew&#93; arrange all.<lb/></p>
            <p>With my best wishes and regards<lb/> to yourself and family<lb/>
                I am yours truly<lb/>
                Dr. H. Vidaver<lb/>
                368 W. 35. Str<lb/>
                New York July 1. 69<lb/></p>
            
        </body>
